    "summary": "The Rosetta Stone (196 BC) was a decree inscribed on a granodiorite stele by priests of the [[event:1040|Ptolemaic Kingdom]] during the reign of Ptolemy V Epiphanes, recording a priestly council's confirmation of royal cult honors in three scripts: ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs, Demotic script, and Greek. It was discovered by French soldiers during Napoleon's Egyptian campaign in 1799 and became the key that unlocked the long-lost ability to read ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs.\n\nThe decree itself was unremarkable — a list of honors to the king and privileges granted to the priesthood — but its parallel inscriptions in three scripts, including Greek which scholars could still read, provided the bilingual key that allowed Jean-François Champollion to crack hieroglyphic writing in 1822, opening the entire civilization of ancient Egypt to direct reading for the first time in over a thousand years. The stone is now in the British Museum in London, where it remains the most visited object in the collection. Its name has entered common use as a metaphor for any tool that provides the key to an otherwise impenetrable subject.",
